        output='# Connectivity Segment — MD&A: FY2025 vs. FY2024\n\n## Revenue Drivers\n\n**Total Connectivity revenue** for FY2025 increased by **$3,788 million, or 49.8%**, compared to FY2024.\n\n| Driver | Change | Detail |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Consumer subscribers** | **+$2,377 million** | Composed of **99.9% growth** in Starlink Subscribers (from 4.4 million to 8.9 million), offset by an **11.2% decline** in Starlink Subscriber ARPU (from $91/month to $81/month), primarily due to international expansion and the addition of lower-priced service plans |\n| **Enterprise & government** | **+$1,411 million** | Driven by growth in enterprise connectivity of **$1,218 million** (including mobile connectivity growth of **$632 million**) and government connectivity growth of **$193 million** |\n\n---\n\n## Cost Structure\n\n### Cost of Revenue\nIncreased by **$1,153 million, or 24.2%**, driven by:\n\n| Component | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| Depreciation from capitalized launch & satellite costs | +$827 million |\n| Ground operating costs | +$134 million |\n| Freight costs | +$72 million |\n| Payment processor fees | +$45 million |\n| International expansion | +$44 million |\n| Warranty costs | +$38 million |\n| Employee compensation (salaries, benefits, SBC) | +$12 million |\n\n**Cost of revenue components** include: depreciation (launch, satellite, ground infrastructure), Starlink Kit costs, shipping/handling, ground operating expenses, employee compensation, payment processor fees, warranty, inventory excess/obsolescence, and customs/duties.\n\n### Research & Development\nIncreased by **$122 million, or 27.1%**, primarily due to:\n- Next-generation satellite production development: **+$84 million**\n- Starlink Kits: **+$22 million**\n- Ground equipment: **+$15 million**\n\n### Selling, General & Administrative\nIncreased by **$135 million, or 40.4%**, primarily due to:\n- Higher marketing costs: **+$53 million**\n- Higher international expansion costs: **+$37 million**\n- Higher allocated general & administrative expenses\n\n### Impairment\nDecreased by **$39 million** compared to FY2024, primarily related to the **discontinuation of a Starlink Kit production line**.\n\n---\n\n## Operating Performance\n\n| Metric | FY2025 | FY2024 | Change | % Change |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Income from operations** | **$4,423 million** | **$2,006 million** | **+$2,417 million** | **120.4%** |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$7,168 million** | **$3,849 million** | **+$3,319 million** | **86.2%** |\n| Starlink Subscribers | 8.9 million | 4.4 million | +4.5 million | 99.9% |\n| Starlink ARPU | $81/month | $91/month | –$10/month | (11.2%) |\n\n### Key Drivers of Operating Income Growth\nThe 120.4% increase in operating income was primarily driven by:\n1. **Revenue outpacing cost growth** — revenue grew 49.8% while cost of revenue grew only 24.2%, demonstrating **significant cost leverage**\n2. **Subscriber base doubling** — nearly 2× subscriber growth (4.4M → 8.9M) spread fixed infrastructure costs across a much larger base\n3. **Enterprise adoption** — $1.4 billion incremental enterprise revenue contributed to margin expansion\n4. **Declining impairment charges** — $39 million reduction year-over-year\n\nPartially offset by:\n- Higher depreciation from accelerated satellite launches ($827 million)\n- Marketing and international expansion costs to drive subscriber growth\n- Higher R&D costs for next-generation product development\n\n### Cost Leverage Analysis\nThe data reveals strong operating leverage: **revenue grew nearly 50% while the cost base grew at roughly half that rate**, with cost of revenue up only 24.2%. This drove operating income margins from approximately 26.4% (FY2024) to approximately 38.8% (FY2025) — a **~1,240 basis point expansion** — illustrating the scalability of the satellite constellation network as subscriber density improved relative to the fixed satellite infrastructure cost base.',
